\title{Cross-isobath translation of nonlinear eddies over steep topography}
\hypersetup{
  pdfkeywords={},
  pdfsubject={},
  pdfcreator={Emacs 24.3.1 (Org mode 8.2.10)}}
\begin{document}

\maketitle
\begin{abstract}
Can continental slope-like topography prevent a deep-water eddy from reaching the shelfbreak? The extent to which an eddy can penetrate the continental slope is expected to control how much water it can transport across the shelfbreak. A series of numerical experiments wherein a surface-intensified anticyclonic eddy interacts with idealized sub-surface shelf-slope topography are used to answer the question. The study is motivated by observations of Gulf Stream warm core rings translating near the shelfbreak off the northeastern United States.

When the eddy is wider than the slope, its edge always gets to the shelfbreak. Then the controlling parameter is the ratio of shelfbreak depth to eddy vertical scale. When the eddy is much deeper than the shelfbreak (warm core ring limit), it cannot cross onto the shelf. Instead, it moves parallel to the shelfbreak, driving a significant offshore flux of shelf water and slowly leaking its own mass onto the slope. In the limit where the shelfbreak is deeper than the eddy, the topography acts like a ridge and causes dramatic eddy splitting across the shelfbreak.

When the eddy's radius is small compared to the slope width, the cross-isobath motion of the eddy is eventually arrested over the slope. In this case, the governing parameter is the ratio, (planetary beta / topographic beta). The eddy evolves to a quasi-equilibrium state where bottom pressure torques balance the integrated angular momentum of the eddy. Then, as predicted by the theorem of Flierl, Stern \& Whitehead (1983), the eddy translates parallel to an isobath, losing energy at a much slower rate to wave radiation.
\end{abstract}
