\subsubsection*{General introduction}
\label{sec-2-0-2}
Mesoscale eddies are found everywhere in the ocean. They move primarily westwards \citep{Chelton2011}; and eventually, some of them must come up against the continental margins or mid-ocean ridges and seamounts. What happens then? Prior work looking at this question can be classified into three types viz., eddies interacting with western boundaries (vertical walls and shelf-like topography), eddies interacting with ridges and seamounts, and the behaviour of eddies over slopes. I shall tackle each of these in turn.
\subsubsection*{Eddies and western boundaries}
\label{sec-2-0-3}
\label{sec:introboundary}
\paragraph*{General observational motivation is cross-shelfbreak exchange.}
\label{sec-2-0-3-1}
The prime reason for studying the eddy-western boundary problem is to understand the impact of eddy-continental shelf interactions on shelf water budgets. For example, in the Mid-Atlantic Bight, \citet{Lentz2010} estimates that an onshore salt flux of \SI[mode=text]{7e-3}\{kg m$^{\text{-2}}$s$^{\text{-2}}$\} across the shelfbreak (\SI{100}{m} isobath) is required to explain observed mean salinity gradients. Hypothesized causes for such a flux are many: (CITATIONS) . Here, we focus only on eddy induced exchange.

The Gulf Stream meanders and sheds warm core rings (WCRs) which move westward and hit the continental slope (henceforth, the slope). Thereafter the rings move southwestwards parallel to the shelf-break, advecting cold, fresh shelf water offshore across the shelfbreak (Figure \ref{fig:WCRSST}) and pushing warm,salty Gulf Stream water onto the shelf \citep{Lee2010}. There are many observations of these fluxes \citep[for e.g.][]{Houghton1986,Garfield1987,Joyce1992, Lee2010, Cenedese2013}. Similar fluxes have also been noted in the Gulf of Mexico \citep{Frolov2004}, the Gulf of Alaska \citep{Okkonen2003, Ladd2007}, the Mozambique channel \citep{Roberts2014}, off the Spanish coast \citep{Peliz2004}, in the Black \citep{Shapiro2010, Zhou2014} and the Bering Sea \citep{Mizobata2006}. Recent work off Greenland has also documented similar exchanges, termed "spilling events", of dense shelf water across the East Greenland shelfbreak caused by bottom intensified cyclones \citep{Magaldi2011, Harden2014}.
\paragraph*{{\bfseries\sffamily ADD} More Locations}
\label{sec-2-0-3-2}
\begin{itemize}
\item Aghulas - \citet{Baker-Yeboah2009}
\end{itemize}
\paragraph*{{\bfseries\sffamily FIXUP} Interactions with vertical wall}
\label{sec-2-0-3-3}
\label{sec:introwall}
\begin{itemize}
\item What have these studies noted?
\label{sec-2-0-3-3-1}
Motivated by these observations, previous research has focused on three questions: how does the eddy translate during and after the impact; how does it react to the presence of the wall; and what circulation patterns result? Briefly, the eddy has been seen to move either in the Kelvin wave direction; in the opposite direction (possibly due to the image effect); or not at all.
\item Describe studies
\label{sec-2-0-3-3-2}
Initial studies of these questions looked at the interaction of eddies with vertical walls over a flat bottom; with particular focus on the along-wall translation of the eddy after the impact. \citet{Nof1988} was the first to point out that during the interaction, eddies leak fluid along a wall which makes them translate along the wall, like a rocket. The numerical experiments in \citet{Shi1993} exhibited the same behaviour. \citet{Shi1994} found that an initially circular eddy transformed into a D-like shape, termed "wodon\footnote{wall + modon}", as its streamlines adjusted to the presence of a wall -- a quasi-geostrophic (QG) representation of the image effect. Yet, \citet{Nof1999} found that in a reduced gravity model, non-linear zero potential vorticity (PV) lenses did not move meridionally at all after interacting with a western wall. Instead, that eddy continuously moved into the wall while simultaneously losing mass from its core. For more details, the reader is referred to the excellent summary and analysis in \citet{Nof1999}.
\end{itemize}
\paragraph*{Shelf-like topography modelling}
\label{sec-2-0-3-4}
\label{sec:introshelf}
\begin{itemize}
\item What have these studies noted?
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-1}
With the addition of shelf-slope like topography, the evolution becomes more complicated. The advection of fluid across isobaths spins up secondary cyclones, in both near-surface and deep layers. These cyclones then interact with the original eddy, forming a dipolar system, resulting in a complicated looping trajectory. Further, intuition based on the behaviour of vortices over a $β$ plane (in a barotropic system, shallow water corresponds to higher PV) suggests that anticyclones will move towards the \emph{topographic} south-west, i.e., to deeper water and cyclones will move towards shallow water. Studies have also noted the excitation of topographic waves during the interactions -- this was studied in more detail by \citet{Louis1982} and \citet{Shaw1991}.
\item Linear models
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-2}
\begin{itemize}
\item \citet{Chapman1987} used a superposition of linear waves to model the eddy as a linear, translating pressure disturbance. The eddy structure was not allowed to evolve in time. They found a bottom-intensified narrow jet along the shelfbreak directed downstream in the coastal trapped wave sense (i.e., moving such that shallow water is on the right in the northern hemisphere). \citet{Kelly1988} observed similar behaviour with a steady, linear and dissipative model.
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-2-1}
\item {\bfseries\sffamily ADD} Also, ATW and penetration scale
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-2-2}
\end{itemize}
\item Barotropic models
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-3}
\begin{itemize}
\item \citet{Wang1992} described extensive barotropic and contour-dynamical numerical experiments of an anticyclone interacting with shelf-slope topography. His findings, for example, the spinup of secondary cyclones and the excitement of topographic waves, have held true for all succeeding studies. These will be described more fully in \ref{sec:modelrun}.
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-3-1}
\end{itemize}
\item Two Layer studies
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-4}
\begin{itemize}
\item Quite a lot of work has used two layer models. These works have mostly focused on describing the evolution of flow patterns in the upper and lower layer; the subsequent trajectory of the eddy and it's speed of propagation. \citet{Sutyrin2003}, using a two layer model with a western coast and slope confined to the lower layer, showed that in when the shelfbreak is deep enough, the eddy can cross the shelfbreak onto the shelf. Subsequently, the eddy moved \emph{northward} when close to coastal wall, in accordance with the image effect. Both \citet{Frolov2004} and \citet{Sutyrin2010} used an intermediate equation two layer model that lets the topography (again, western coast) penetrate into the upper layer. The former study used two active layers while the latter used only one. Interestingly, both papers show the anticyclone moving \emph{southwards} after collision with a western shelf-slope boundary. They claim that if the topography is confined to the lower layer, then the image effect dominates vortex translation. \citet{Sutyrin2003} found that the effectiveness of the image effect depended on the width of the shelf: runs with shelves wider than an eddy radius exhibit weaker image effect-like behaviour. The implication is that the steep slope doesn't induce an image effect but the \emph{coastal wall} does. All of the above studies also described decay due to Rossby wave radiation with decay rate being proportional to the Rossby wave speed.
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-4-1}
\item {\bfseries\sffamily ADD} Experiments with point vortices have found that anticyclones tend to repelled away from step like topography, while cyclones are attracted.
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-4-2}
\item \citet{White2004} looked at point vortices in a two-layer model where topography penetrated into the upper layer.
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-4-3}
\item \citet{Zhang2011}, in a novel study using a contour dynamics model, studied export of water out of a bay i.e., step like topography with a curved coast.
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-4-4}
\end{itemize}
\item Continuously stratified models
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-5}
\begin{itemize}
\item Comparatively less work has utilized continuously stratified models. \citet{Oey2004} initialized their anticyclone over a slope and observed a bottom-intensified jet similar to that noted in \citet{Chapman1987}. Something about upwelling and downwelling.
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-5-1}
\item \citet{Hyun2008} shows eddy's progress across slope being arrested in one case. Mostly qualitative discussion, some exploration of parameter space.
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-5-2}
\item Both \citet{Hyun2008, Wei2009} started their eddies in deep water and described the subsequent evolution.
\label{sec-2-0-3-4-5-3}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Eddies v/s ridge / seamount}
\label{sec-2-0-4}
\label{sec:introseamount}
\paragraph*{The second class of studies looks the collision of eddies with mid-ocean ridges and seamounts. This is motivated mainly by two sets of observations:collisions of Aghulas rings with Walvis ridge in the south-eastern Atlantic \citep{Baker-Yeboah2008} and the collision of Meddies\footnote{Mediterranean eddies} with mid-ocean seamounts (CITATION).}
\label{sec-2-0-4-1}
\paragraph*{van Geffen papers}
\label{sec-2-0-4-2}
\paragraph*{Aghulas rings and Walvis ridge: \citet{Kamenkovich1996} + obs papers}
\label{sec-2-0-4-3}
\paragraph*{\citet{ZavalaSanson2002}}
\label{sec-2-0-4-4}
\begin{itemize}
\item barotropic cyclones moving towards ridge
\label{sec-2-0-4-4-1}
\item sees splitting across thin ridges.
\label{sec-2-0-4-4-2}
\item β$_{\text{r}}$ > β$_{\text{p}}$ unlike van Geffen papers where β$_{\text{p}}$ < β$_{\text{r}}$
\label{sec-2-0-4-4-3}
\end{itemize}
\paragraph*{Beismann et al. (1999)}
\label{sec-2-0-4-5}
\paragraph*{Meddies and mid-Atlantic ridge: ?}
\label{sec-2-0-4-6}
\paragraph*{Laboratory simulations: brief mention? - not really relevant?}
\label{sec-2-0-4-7}
\begin{itemize}
\item \citet{Adduce2004} - splitting up of barotropic vortices
\label{sec-2-0-4-7-1}
\item \citet{Cenedese2002} - barotropic vortices with cylinders
\label{sec-2-0-4-7-2}
\item \citet{Cenedese2013} - with shelfbreak current, not relevant to this study
\label{sec-2-0-4-7-3}
