\label{sec-2-0-4-7-4}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Eddies over slopes}
\label{sec-2-0-5}
\label{sec:introslope}
The third class of studies comprises those that look that the evolution of eddies over (sometimes, infinite) slopes. These have focused on wave radiation dispersing the vortec structure. \citet{Smith1983} were among the first to study the problem with a two layer non-linear model. They suggest that the behaviour of barotropic vortices over topography on a beta plane can be predicted as the vector resultant of the self-advection tendencies of the eddy due to planetary beta ($β$)  and topographic beta ($β_t \sim f_0/H\, ∇H$). \citet{Grimshaw1994} also conducted two layer simulations and found that the eddy initial tended to move towards a topographic south-west. After day one, the eddy was seen to radiate a lot of its energy as coastally trapped waves. \citet{LaCasce1998} explored the problem with a two layer quasi-geostrophic (QG) model with a sloping bottom on a $f$ plane. He found that over gentle slopes (high $U_2/β_tL^2$), the eddy moved towards the topographic south-west, whereas, over steep slopes, the lower layer signal radiated away as topographic Rossby waves leaving behind an upper layer eddy. He concluded that the results of \citet{Smith1983} held over gentle slopes but not over steep ones \citep[see also][]{LaCasce1996}. \citet{Thierry1999} used a two layer model to evaluate when reduced gravity models are appropriate. They found that this approximation worked well over steep slopes i.e., when the lower layer radiates away.

\citet{Jacob2002} undertook a detailed exploration of the problem using a two layer primitive equation model studying four slope orientations (coasts at the north, south, east and west). When the eddy had significant barotropic signal, they explained their results as being a consequence of the competition between $β$ and $β_t$. If $β_t$ is in the same sense as that of $β$ (northern coast), then the eddy loses a lot of energy to radiation and moves southwestwards geographically. If they oppose each other (southern coast), they observed translation to the geographic southwest when $β > β_t$, very little meridional translation when $β=-β_t$ and translation to topographic southwest when $β<β_t$. I estimate their eddy's Rhines numbers to be $\sim \mO(25)$, which puts them squarely in the weak slope self-advection regime of \citet{LaCasce1998}. For compensated eddies, they find that the "evolution is minimally influenced by topography", agreeing with \citet{Smith1983} and \citet{Kamenkovich1996}. In all these studies, the bottom does not intersect the upper layer.

\paragraph*{\citet{Sutyrin2001} derived an asymptotic theory for lower layer behaviour over steep slopes. This was extended to a strongly non-uniform slope in \citet{Sutyrin2009}.}
\label{sec-2-0-5-1}

\paragraph*{:noexport:\citet{Sutyrin2001} used an asymptotic expansion in $ε = βL/f_0$ to show that planetary $β$ induced cross-slope motion causes stretching and compression in the lower layer forming dipolar gyres that result in additional along-isobath velocities. His theory is valid when the bottom slope is strong enough that fast radiation brings the lower-layer to a quasi-stable state quite quickly.}
\label{sec-2-0-5-2}
\subsubsection*{Scope of this paper}
\label{sec-2-0-6}
To summarize, then, there is still uncertainty about the direction of motion of the eddy after the initial impact.

The central goal of this thesis is to understand the contribution of offshore-eddy driven fluxes to the net shelfbreak exchange problem. The scenario envisioned here is one where a surface-intensified deep-water eddy (say, created by the instability of a western boundary current) migrates towards the continental slope. Prior to looking at fluxes across the shelfbreak, we need to know how close the eddy gets to the shelfbreak. Specifically, is there a regime where an eddy can be prevented from crossing the slope? The rubric here is to check whether the eddy can drive large enough exchanges across the shelf. If not, the slope has arrested its progress.

If we assume that the \emph{initial} bottom velocity signal is very small, the deep-water eddy should behave as on a flat bottom $β$ plane and move south-westwards. If this motion results in it crossing isobaths, eventually the water depth will decrease enough that the deep velocity signal will be substantial i.e., in some sense, the eddy is now more barotropic. The two layer model results described in Section \ref{sec:introslope} suggest that if the slope is steep, this deep signal of the eddy should continuously radiate away. This suggests that the slope does not oppose the cross-isobath motion of the eddy and that the eddy will eventually reach the shelfbreak, driving significant fluxes across it. \emph{However}, if an appropriately defined Rhines-like number for the deep flow becomes large enough, perhaps the slope will prevent cross-isobath motion\footnote{For anticyclones over topography with western and eastern coasts, this would also indicate motion away from the shelfbreak.}. This was observed in the $β=-β_t$ case (southern coast; their experiment B4) of \citet{Jacob2002}. It is difficult, \emph{a priori}, to decide which of these two outcomes hold true when a surface intensified eddy moves across isobaths in a continuously stratified model. Will these two layer ideas extend to a stratified system?

Using fully non-linear, continuously stratified simulations, we will show that there is a regime where topography can arrest the cross-isobath motion of an eddy. We will also derive a scaling that predicts the water depth at which this arrest happens.
\paragraph*{{\bfseries\sffamily CANCELLED} To simplify, we will ignore the presence of a shelfbreak front.}
\label{sec-2-0-6-1}
\paragraph*{{\bfseries\sffamily CANCELLED} Cross-shelfbreak fluxes and leakage from eddy will be treated in a future paper.}
\label{sec-2-0-6-2}
\paragraph*{{\bfseries\sffamily CANCELLED} Summarize earlier literature}
\label{sec-2-0-6-3}
\paragraph*{{\bfseries\sffamily CANCELLED} Primarily an extension of \citet{Wang1992}.}
\label{sec-2-0-6-4}
\section{Model setup}
\label{sec-3}
\subsubsection*{ROMS equations}
\label{sec-3-0-1}
We use an idealized configuration of the Regional Ocean Modeling System \citep{Shchepetkin2005}. The model solves the equations:

\begin{align}
\label{eq:eqroms}
    u_t + uu_x + vu_y + wu_z - fv &= \frac{1}{ρ_0}  p_x + τ^x_z + A_H (u_{xx} + u_{yy}) + A_v u_{zz} \\
    v_t + uv_x + vv_y + wv_z + fu &= \frac{1}{ρ_0}  p_y + τ^y_z + A_H (v_{xx} + v_{yy}) + A_v v_{zz} \\
    0 &= p_z - ρg \\
    u_x + v_y + w_z &= 0 \\
    ρ_t + uρ_x + vρ_y + wρ_z &= 0
\end{align}

The main elements of the problem viz., shelf-slope topography, anticyclonic eddy and stratification, are all reduced to the simplest possible form.
\subsubsection*{Figure showing initial condition\hfill{}\textsc{fig}}
\label{sec-3-0-2}
\subsubsection*{Eddy shape}
\label{sec-3-0-3}
The eddy is prescribed as a radially symmetric, surface intensified, Gaussian temperature anomaly superimposed on background stratification ($N^2$) according to

\begin{equation}
\label{eq:tanom}
T_\text{edd} = T_\text{amp} \exp{\left[-(r/R)^2 - (z/H)^2\right]}
\end{equation}

The horizontal length scale, $R$ is specified and the vertical scale, $H$, is determined as $H = fL/N$. Cyclo-geostrophic balance is used to determine the velocity field by prescribing zero velocity at the bottom. For most of the runs described here, the background stratification ($N^2$) is constant. We will look at the effects of an exponential $N^2$ profile in Section \ref{sec:N2}.

The eddy is initially located in deep water far enough from the topography (Figure \texttt{fig:initial}) so that its initial evolution is indistinguishable from that over a flat bottomed ocean. The intent here is to have our artificially prescribed eddy adjust to the $β$-plane in deep (as compared to eddy vertical scale) water before it starts interacting with the continental slope. To track material within the eddy, we initialize a dye with value 1 where the temperature anomaly is greater than some small value. In practice, not all of the dye is carried with the eddy but this conservative initial distribution lets us identify an eddy core that transports mass over long spatial and time scales.

Anticyclonic eddies move both westwards and southwards when placed on a β-plane \citep{McWilliams1979, Nof1983, Early2011}. We use this southward tendency to direct the eddy towards the topography, located at the southern edge of the domain.
\subsubsection*{why southern coast?}
\label{sec-3-0-4}
Section \ref{sec:west} looks at the problem with a western coast. In this manner, cross-isobath motion is accomplished without the use of a cross-isobath background flow. A future paper will examine the same question with the addition of a shelf-break front. Maintaining a \emph{stable} meridional front on a β-plane is tricky (CITE PEDLOSKY PAPER) and so, we will use a zonal front. To facilitate comparison, we focus zonally oriented topography in this paper.
\subsubsection*{Topography}
\label{sec-3-0-5}
The topography is constructed using three straight lines representing the shelf, the continental slope and the deep ocean respectively. This allows easy control of the topographic slopes for both the continental shelf and slope. The deep ocean is always flat. A four point running mean is used six times to smooth the intersection of these lines at the shelfbreak and slopebreak. The term "slopebreak" will refer to the intersection of the continental slope and the flat bottomed deep ocean.
\subsubsection*{Boundary Conditions + sponge layers}
\label{sec-3-0-6}
The southern boundary is closed so as to represent the coast. The other three boundaries are open. For these, we use an explicit Chapman condition for the free-surface and a modified Flather boundary conditions \citep{Mason2010} for 2D momentum. For 3D momentum and tracers, we use an Orlanski radiation condition. To prevent noise at the open boundary from contaminating the solution, we use sponge layers -- \SI{50}{km} wide regions with lateral Laplacian viscosity linearly increasing from 0 to \SI{50}{m^2/s^2} -- as damping.
\subsubsection*{Viscosity + resolution}
\label{sec-3-0-7}
A biharmonic lateral viscosity along s-surfaces is used to control noise outside the sponge layers. The horizontal grid resolution is \SI{1}{km} in $x$ and $y$. Experiments with a \SI{750}{m} grid show no difference in the diagnostics we used. For computational efficiency, we use a hyperbolic tangent function to stretch the grid spacing near the sponge layers at the open boundaries. Maximum grid spacing is \SI{1.8}{km}. Runs with and without this stretching showed no difference in our diagnostics. In the vertical, we always use 72 grid points distributed such that vertical grid spacing is smallest near the surface and largest near the bottom. A density Jacobian based algorithm \citep{Shchepetkin2003} is used to reduce pressure gradient error (ROMS option \texttt{DJ\_GRADPS}).
\subsubsection*{Strategy}
\label{sec-3-0-8}
\paragraph*{We will look at southern coast first. Why?}
\label{sec-3-0-8-1}
\begin{itemize}
\item competition of $β$ and $β_t$.
\label{sec-3-0-8-1-0-1}
\item Instability of background flow, but there is no background flow now.
\label{sec-3-0-8-1-0-2}
\item Instability of eventual shelfbreak front model.
\label{sec-3-0-8-1-0-3}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{{\bfseries\sffamily CANCELLED} Not lens-like}
\label{sec-3-0-9}
\begin{itemize}
\item This agrees with cross-sections through WCRs (Line W cruises).
\label{sec-3-0-9-0-1}
\item \url{http://www.whoi.edu/science/PO/linew/images/propertysect/sections.2009sep.gn.jpg}
\label{sec-3-0-9-0-2}
\end{itemize}
\section{Typical model run}
\label{sec-4}
\label{sec:modelrun}
\subsubsection*{Figure 2 : (x,y) plot of typical model run\hfill{}\textsc{fig}}
\label{sec-4-0-1}
\paragraph*{with dye contours, eddy track, detected eddy core and shelf water cyclones}
\label{sec-4-0-1-1}
\subsubsection*{Figure 3 : (y,z) cross-section of eddy and smaller cyclones/anticyclones\hfill{}\textsc{fig}}
\label{sec-4-0-2}
\subsubsection*{Do I address similarities with vertical wall studies here or later?}
\label{sec-4-0-3}
\subsubsection*{General description - Steep slope}
\label{sec-4-0-4}
\paragraph*{Along-isobath translation velocity increases at this point due to "rocket effect" of Nof (xxxx) papers. \citet{Sutyrin2009} might have observed this, though he has an alternate explanation. Contrary to assertion in \citet{Nof1996} but he says topography is as important as β}
\label{sec-4-0-4-1}
\paragraph*{Text}
\label{sec-4-0-4-2}
When the model is integrated, we initially see the radiation of internal waves as the eddy adjusts. The anticyclonic eddy begins to move westwards and southwards as it spins up β-gyres \citep{Sutyrin1994, Early2011} and radiates Rossby waves \citep{Flierl1984, Flierl1994, Chassignet1991, Jacob2002}. Eventually after about 60 days, it crosses the slope-break and interacts with the sloping topography. Distortions in the shape of the eddy appear as its streamlines adjust to the presence of the boundary. This is reminiscent of the wodon shape in the quasi-geostrophic results of \citet{Shi1994}. The eddy moves westwards (or upstream in the coastal-trapped wave sense), as expected from the rocket and image effects \citep{Nof1999}. Since $β/β_t \sim \SI{1e-2}{}$, this contradicts the results of \citet{Jacob2002} and \citet{Smith1983}. The eddy's cross-isobath progress is arrested when its shore-ward (southern) edge reaches the shelfbreak and proceeds to move upstream (westwards) with its center roughly following the same isobath. The interaction is dramatic: filaments of shelf water are forcefully pulled offshore -- in some cases, these form cyclones that are flung eastwards by the eddy; and the eddy intermittently loses mass from its core -- a leakage that forms \citep{Shi1993, Nof1999} many small vortices that moves downstream (in the coastally-trapped wave sense) towards the open eastern boundary. This leakage is visible at the surface \ref{fig:???} contrary to the speculation of \citet{Nof1999}. We see the along-isobath translation velocity of the eddy increase as it loses mass from the core, as expected from the rocket effect.

The small shelf water cyclones are similar to those noted by \citet{Kennelly1985} around the Gulf Stream Warm Core Ring 82B and seen in the Gulf of Mexico \citep{Frolov2004}. Interactions of these cyclones and the big eddy result in a looping motion of the eddy center as was noted by \citet{Frolov2004}.
\subsubsection*{Contrast with shallow slope run}
\label{sec-4-0-5}
\paragraph*{Cross-isobath velocity is a lot slower.}
\label{sec-4-0-5-1}
\paragraph*{Show ew-64361 where eddy is stopped quite far away from the shelfbreak.}
\label{sec-4-0-5-2}
\paragraph*{Text}
\label{sec-4-0-5-3}
The shallow slope run is initialized with an eddy of the same size as in the steep slope case. Since this eddy is of deformation radius size, the shallow slope is a lot wider. For now, it is sufficient to note that the cross-isobath motion of the eddy is a lot slower in this case, and in some cases, the eddy never reaches the shelfbreak. This will be discussed in more detail in Section \texttt{sec:bigslope}.
\subsubsection*{North-South isobath run.}
\label{sec-4-0-6}
\subsubsection*{Observational comparisons?}
\label{sec-4-0-7}
