\section{Non-dimensional parameters and diagnostics}
\label{sec-5}
\label{sec:nondimdiag}
\subsection*{Eddy tracking and diagnostics}
\label{sec-5-1}
\label{sec:diag}
\subsubsection*{Tracking - add figure showing both contours?}
\label{sec-5-1-1}
The eddy is tracked using the method described in \citet{Chelton2011} with slight modifications appropriate for the much easier task of tracking a single large anticyclone. This method lets us detect a simply connected region within a closed SSH contour containing a SSH maximum (or minimum for a cyclone). Within this SSH contour, the closed contour with zero relative vorticity at the surface is defined to contain the \emph{core} of the  eddy. As in \citet{Early2011}, we see that this zero vorticity contour well represents mass (dye) that is transported by the eddy. A density anomaly (with respect to background stratification) associated with this zero vorticity contour at $t=0$ is used to identify the eddy's core in three dimensions. This method is seen to successfully track dyed water that is transported in the eddy throughout the simulation.
\subsubsection*{SSH contour is crap. RV is better but not good enough to detect edge of the eddy. So we use the center.}
\label{sec-5-1-2}
Using the vorticity contour to define the eddy is more robust because the initially detected SSH contour confuses Rossby wave signals with the eddy signal and identifies a much larger area than is seen to transport dye over long times. However, the edges of the contour are sensitive to eddy splitting (as part of the leakage described in Section \texttt{sec:desc)}.
\subsubsection*{Define center and use it for vertical scale}
\label{sec-5-1-3}
This is defined as the location of the SSH maximum within the detected vorticity contours. It was found to be more robust than using a SSH-weighted centroid as the latter is significantly influenced by the size of the detected contour. A Gaussian fit to the vertical profile of the temperature \emph{anomaly} at the eddy's center to diagnose its vertical scale $D$. This agrees well with the 3D structure of the density anomaly criterion described earlier.
\subsubsection*{more eddy parameters}
\label{sec-5-1-4}
The eddy's radius ($R$) is defined as the radius of a circle having the same area as that enclosed by the zero relative vorticity contour. This corresponds to the diagnostic $L_s$ in \citet{Chelton2011}. The eddy's velocity scale, ($U$), is defined as the mean of the velocity values on the identified zero relative vorticity contour.
\subsubsection*{Energy}
\label{sec-5-1-5}
The eddy's potential and kinetic energies are calculated as
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:edden}
\text{PE} = \quad ; \quad \text{KE} =
\end{equation}

\subsection*{Non-dimensional numbers}
\label{sec-5-2}
\label{sec:nondim}
\subsubsection*{Definitions}
\label{sec-5-2-1}
Using the detected zero relative vorticity contour, the eddy's Rossby and Rhines numbers as

\begin{equation}
\label{eq:nondim}
\Ro = \frac{⟨v_x - u_y⟩}{f_0} \; \quad \; \Rh = \frac{U}{βR²}
\end{equation}

where, $⟨v_x - u_y⟩$ represents an area average of the relative vorticity at the surface, $f_0$ is the Coriolis parameter (generally \SI{5e-5}\{s$^{\text{-1}}$\} here); planetary $β = \dr f/\dr y$; $U, R$ are the velocity and length scales of the eddy as defined above. Typical values for a Gulf Stream warm core ring are $\Ro \sim 0.12$ \citep{Olson1991} and $\Rh \sim 12$.

\subsubsection*{Rossby number}
\label{sec-5-2-2}
In the rest of the ocean, rings seem to have $\Ro \sim 0.05 \text{--} 0.20$ \citep{Olson1991}. There is an upper bound on the Rossby number for an anticyclonic ring that arises as follows. Cyclo-geostrophic balance in radial co-ordinates results in a quadratic equation for the velocity field. For real solutions, the Rossby number calculated using a \emph{geostrophic} velocity must be less than 0.25. When calculated as in \ref{eq:nondim}, the upper limit is around 0.28. This corresponds to a maximum Rossby number of 1 somewhere within the eddy.

\subsubsection*{Rhines Number}
\label{sec-5-2-3}
Nearly all model runs presented here start with an eddy Rhines number $\sim 12$. The eddy's Rhines number influences the rate at which the eddy loses energy initially to Rossby wave radiation, a process that results in decreasing eddy radius \citep{Flierl1984}. For $\Rh \sim 1$, the eddy disperses into Rossby waves and ceases to exist as a coherent structure. For higher values, there is gradually lesser loss of energy in deep water. Here, we are interested in the eddy's evolution over the slope and so, the Rhines number is held constant.

\subsubsection*{Burger numbers}
\label{sec-5-2-4}
The shelf and slope Burger numbers are defined as
\[ S_α = \frac{αN}{f_0} \]
where $α$ is the bottom slope of the shelf or slope respectively and $N$ is a representative value of the background stratification.

\section{Results}
\label{sec-6}
\subsection*{Can sloping topography stop an eddy from crossing it?}
\label{sec-6-1}
\subsubsection*{General description}
\label{sec-6-1-1}
\label{sec:trackdesc}
\paragraph*{Table 1 : table of run parameters\hfill{}\textsc{tab}}
\label{sec-6-1-1-1}
\paragraph*{Figure : eddy center tracks of the following runs\hfill{}\textsc{fig}}
\label{sec-6-1-1-2}
\begin{figure}[htb]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/paper1/centrack.pdf}
\caption{\label{fig:centrack}Will the eddy always reach the shelfbreak? These are tracks of the eddy center for four runs with different values of $L_{sl}/L$, i.e, (slope width)/(eddy radius). In (a) -- southern coast -- $x$ and $y$ axes are relative to the eddy's initial location and location of the shelfbreak respectively. Both axes are normalized by the initial radius of the eddy. In two cases, the eddy is stopped away from the shelfbreak, while in the other two, the eddy's edge gets to the shelfbreak. Dots, marked every 75 days, indicate a slowdown of cross-isobath motion in these two cases. The cross indicates the location that we try to parameterize with \ref{eq:erfparam}. In (b) -- western coast -- the (x,y) axes are normalized by the location of the shelfbreak and the eddy's initial location respectively.}
\end{figure}
\paragraph*{Text}
\label{sec-6-1-1-3}
The goal is to understand whether the shoreward edge of the eddy's core can reach the end of the slope. Here, all simulations have a shelf, and so, the question becomes, can sloping topography prevent the water in the eddy's core from reaching the shelfbreak? There is nothing special about the shelf-break here other than that it refers to the end of the slope.

Figure \ref{fig:centrack} shows tracks of the eddy's center (SSH maximum) for multiple runs.  Co-ordinates of the center are relative to the eddy's initial location in $x$ and the shelf-break location in $y$. The axes are normalized by the eddy's initial radius. If, in Figure \ref{fig:centrack}, the center reaches a $y$ location that is one eddy radius away from the shelfbreak (gray dashed line), then its southern edge has reached the shelfbreak. Using the center location as a diagnostic is more robust as it avoids the uncertainty associated with the contour detection algorithm. However, tracks of the eddy center are sensitive to the Rhines number of the eddy. Lower $\Rh$ eddies radiate more energy, leading to a decrease in radius. So if we had two runs with different $\Rh$ that both reach the shelfbreak, one will have lesser radius than the other and it's center will seem to have penetrated more. To avoid this, we keep the $\Rh ~ 12$ in most of the runs here. Exceptions will be pointed out later.

Bottom slope, slope width and eddy Rossby numbers were all varied to produce the tracks in Figure \ref{fig:centrack}. The cross on each track in Figure \ref{fig:centrack} represents the location at which the eddy's cross-isobath translation has decreased significantly. This location will be used later to verify our proposed scaling. To diagnose this, we fit the function, \[ y - y_\text{ref} = y_0 \tanh{\left(\frac{t-t_\text{ref}}{T}\right)} + y_1 \left(\frac{t - t_\text{ref}}{T}\right), \] to the eddy center latitude for each run. The location of the eddy at $t - t_\text{ref} = 1.5T$ then gives us the location at which the cross-isobath motion has been considerably reduced. In most cases (refer to tracks), this happens when the eddy's edge has reached the shelfbreak, which, if not deep enough (see Section \ref{sec:sb}), acts like a vertical wall. However, one particular eddy seems to have been stopped quite far away. This happens in the limit where the eddy's horizontal scale is smaller than the slope's width; a regime where the two layer results of \citet{LaCasce1998} and \citet{Jacob2002} might have been expected to apply.
\subsubsection*{Eddy scale < slope width}
\label{sec-6-1-2}
\paragraph*{Eddy can be stopped far away from shelfbreak. Point to track of ew-64361 in Figure 4.}
\label{sec-6-1-2-1}
\paragraph*{Short derivation of Flierl, Stern \& Whitehead theorem}
\label{sec-6-1-2-2}
As described in Section \texttt{sec:introsl}, the two layer model results lead us to believe that for steep enough slopes, the lower layer signal radiates away and the eddy should continually translate across isobaths as long as slope width is not a factor. Track XXX in Figure \ref{fig:centrack} indicates that this is not the case.

The two layer studies indicate that understanding the nature of wave radiation from eddies is crucial to understanding the translation of eddies over slopes. The integrated angular momentum theorem of \citet{Flierl1983} which predicts when radiation is possible is thus, a suitable starting point. The short derivation presented here closely follows that in \citet{Flierl1987}. First integrate the horizontal momentum and continuity equations between two material surfaces ($\int$), $z=s_0(x,y,t)$ to $z=s_1(x,y,t)$. Then, integrate the momentum equations over the entire $x-y$ plane ($\iint$) to get \citep{Flierl1987}
\begin{align}
\label{eq:int}
\ppt \left(s_1 - s_0\right) + \ppx \int u + \ppy \int v &=0 \\
\ppt \iiint u + \iint \ppx \int u^2 + \iint \ppy \int uv - \iint f\int v &= -\iint \ppx \int p + \iint \left(p_{1}s_{1x} - p_{0}s_{0x} \right) \\
\ppt \iiint v + \iint \ppx \int uv + \iint \ppy \int v^2 + \iint f\int u &= -\iint \ppy \int p + \iint \left(p_{1}s_{1y} - p_{0}s_{0y} \right)
\end{align}

No approximations have been used to obtain \ref{eq:int}. $p$ represents the pressure anomaly field of the eddy.  Using Gauss' theorem,
\begin{equation*}
 \iint \ppy \int p = \int \left(\int p \right)\dr{x}\cdot\hat{n}.
\end{equation*}
For a structure that is initially isolated and \emph{remains} isolated, the above RHS contour integral will be zero, a result that holds for the non-linear terms as well. The simplified set of integrated equations for a \emph{isolated} structure is
\begin{align}
\label{eq:simp}
\ppt \left(s_1 - s_0 \right) + \ppx \int u + \ppy \int v &=0 \\
\ppt \iiint u - f_0 \iiint v - β \iint y\int v &= \iint \left(p_{1}s_{1x} - p_{0}s_{0x} \right) \\
\ppt \iiint v + f_0 \iiint u + β \iint y\int u &= \iint \left(p_{1}s_{1y} - p_{0}s_{0y} \right).
\end{align}

This is statement of the integrated force balance on parcels bounded by the two material surfaces. At this point, we must choose our bounding material surfaces. Choosing a material surfaces that defines the boundary of eddy water results in the meridional force balance derived by \citet{Nof1983} viz., a steady westward moving isolated structure has the $β$ force, form stress or "planetary lift" in \citet{Nof1983}, and the Coriolis force on a westward moving mass of water, balance each other. Choosing the material surfaces to be the upper and lower boundaries ($s_0 = -H(x,y)$) of the fluid and making the rigid lid approximation lets us define a transport streamfunction $ψ$ such that
\[ \int u = - ψ_y; \qquad \int v = ψ_x. \]

For an isolated structure, $ψ$ must decay quickly. Something about time-dependent terms. \emph{Assuming} this decay is $\mO (1/r^2)$ results in a much more simplified balance,
\begin{align}
\label{eq:fsw}
0 &=  \iint p_0 \pp Hx \\
c \iint (f_0 + βy)h + β \iint ψ &=  \iint p_0 \pp Hy.
\end{align}

Over a flat bottom, the original theorem put forward in \citet{Flierl1983} viz., $β \iint ψ = 0$ is required. Thus, any \emph{initially} isolated structure that has net angular momentum, like our anticyclone, \emph{must} radiate waves and set up boundary contributions to the integrals in \ref{eq:simp} so that it is satisfied \citep{Flierl1987}. For all runs here, the eddy is initially set to be surface intensified with no bottom velocity (or pressure) signal. This is why we see the radiation of Rossby waves as the eddy initially adjusts to the $β$ plane in deep water.

As the eddy crosses the slope into shallower water, the bottom pressure anomaly increases. Physically, the topography opposes the cross-isobath motion of the eddy via an increasing form stress at the bottom of the eddy, causing a decrease in meridional translation velocity. As time progresses, the eddy's angular momentum will slowly decrease (it is losing energy to radiation) and the bottom pressure anomaly will increase to a point where an approximate balance between the two is possible. \emph{If} this happens, the system is now isolated and the radiation of energy from the eddy will be significantly reduced resulting in longer eddy lifetime. It is important to realize that the theorem tells us nothing of the efficiency of this radiation i.e., it does not predict how quickly the eddy will lose its energy. This point will be discussed later. Another important point is that \ref{eq:fsw} is a necessary but not sufficient condition. \citet{Flierl1983} demonstrated this by deriving additional conditions for a barotropic QG system. Satisfying these additional conditions means that the value of $ψ_t$ on the bounding contour will be even smaller than if only \ref{eq:fsw} was satisfied.

There is no reason to expect this balance to hold exactly. With the eddy losing energy to Rossby waves prior to reaching this \emph{critical} water depth, and the generation of cyclonic features \citep{Wang1992, Oey2004} due to cross-slope advection of water, the integrated momentum balance of the entire domain will be quite complicated. Here, we argue that if the terms in \ref{eq:fsw} are of the similar magnitude, then the system is quasi-isolated and the eddy's core now acts like a coherent structure, with very slow radiative energy loss. The cross-isobath motion is then significantly arrested.

\uline{This meridional force balance also prevents it from further crossing isobaths, resulting in the eddy moving geographically westwards along an isobath.}
\paragraph*{Figure 5: Force diagram - not sure if required\hfill{}\textsc{fig}}
\label{sec-6-1-2-3}
\begin{figure}[htb]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/force-diagram.pdf}
\caption{\label{fig:fbd}Free body diagram for an anticyclonic eddy in the Northern Hemisphere after it has adjusted to slope.  Light gray arrows indicate velocity of eddy center. \emph{Direction of wave drag is unknown!} This is when integrated to the bounding streamline of the eddy (not ∞)}
\end{figure}
\paragraph*{Explain why I'm not doing direct diagnosis}
\label{sec-6-1-2-4}
\paragraph*{Scaling}
\label{sec-6-1-2-5}
Directly diagnosing the balance in \ref{eq:fsw} turns out to be quite hard. It requires choosing a bounding contour that not only minimizes contributions from the Rossby waves radiated initially, but one that also results in the integrated Coriolis ($f_0u$) and pressure gradient ($\pp{}{x}\int p$) terms being very close to zero. It was not possible to find a contour that satisfied both criteria and the diagnosed balance was dominantly geostrophic.

Instead, assuming the balance holds, we can scale both terms in \ref{eq:fsw} to arrive at a relationship and see whether that holds. For velocity scales $U_s$ (surface) and $U_b$ (bottom), vertical scale $L_z$ and horizontal scale $L_x$,
\[ β ψ \sim β U_s L_x L_z; \quad p\bt s_{0y} = \pp Hy f_0 U_b L_x. \]
Assuming that the eddy remains approximately Gaussian throughout the evolution lets us write
\[ \frac{U_b}{U_s} = 1 - \erf{\left(\frac{H}{L_z}\right)}, \] where $H$ is the water depth at the eddy center. Then, our predicted relationship for the water depth $H$ at which we expect the eddy to slow down significantly is
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:erfparam}
1 - \erf{\left(\frac{H}{L_z}\right)} \sim \frac{β}{\frac{f_0}{L_z} \pp Hy} = \frac{β}{β_t},
\end{equation}
with topographic beta defined as $β_t = f_0/L_z^0 H_y$.

Applying this scaling to the model output requires the diagnosis of a point in the eddy's trajectory where its cross-isobath translation velocity has been considerably reduced i.e., this isobath is where \ref{eq:erfparam} probably holds. The hyperbolic tangent fit described in Section \ref{sec:trackdesc} is used to locate this point and the scaling is shown in \cref{fig:penerf}. The $y$ axis shows the LHS calculated using $H$ at the locations marked by crosses in \ref{fig:centrack}.
\paragraph*{Figure 6: Scaling for H/Lz\hfill{}\textsc{fig}}
\label{sec-6-1-2-6}
\begin{figure}[htb]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/penetration-erf-param-tanh-t0.png}
\caption{\label{fig:penerf}\citet{Flierl1983} based scaling for isobath $H$ at which the eddy's cross-isobath motion is appreciably reduced. The unlabeled black crosses are model runs with anticyclones, constant $N^2$ and east-west isobaths. Those labeled $N^2$ have depth-varying $N^2(z)$ (Section\ref{sec:N2}) and those marked with 'C' are runs with cyclones (constant $N^2$) (Section \ref{sec:cyc}). The dashed gray line is the linear fit in \ref{eq:erfparam}.}
\end{figure}
\paragraph*{Figure 7: Show energy decay plot\hfill{}\textsc{fig}}
\label{sec-6-1-2-7}
\begin{itemize}
\item steep and shallow slope with energy decay reducing to half of its initial rate when in shallower water.
\label{sec-6-1-2-7-1}
\end{itemize}
\paragraph*{Can this explain the two layer results?}
\label{sec-6-1-2-8}
The integrated angular momentum theorem for a two layer system (of equal depths) is
\[ β_1 \iint ψ_1 + β_2 \iint ψ_2 = 0  \label{eq:fsw2layer}\]
This is obtained by summing up the PV evolution equation for each layer, multiplying by $x$ and integrating over the domain. Arguments put forward in \citet{Flierl1983} for the barotropic system can be applied resulting in \eqref{eq:fsw2layer}. In \citet{LaCasce1998}, $β_1 = β = 0, β_2 = β_t$, so his barotropic eddies are expected to always radiate waves without ever reaching a quasi-isolated state. Indeed, that is what he observed over steep slopes (small $\frac{U_2}{β_2L^2}$). The lower layer energy radiated away leaving behind a surface intensified vortex. Over gentler slopes (large $\frac{U_2}{β_2L^2}$), he noted translation towards the topographic "south-west". Even though the theorem tells us that the eddy must radiate waves, it does not tell us how quickly the eddy's energy will radiate away. \citet{LaCasce1998} finds that this is governed by a Rhines-like number and \citet{Flierl1984} derived a dependence on $βL/f_0$ for an eddy on a $β$ plane over a flat bottom.

\begin{itemize}
\item \citet{Jacob2002} see center saturate out with southern coast.
\label{sec-6-1-2-8-1}
\item Lesser decay was observed by \citet{Jacob2002} but attribute to opposing β and β$_{\text{t}}$ - FSW is a physical reasoning for this?
\label{sec-6-1-2-8-2}
\citet{Jacob2002} observed a slower cross-isobath translation speed in their 2 layer, primitive equation simulations (their eddy B4) but attributed it to the opposing effects of $β$ and $β_t$. We prefer to interpret in terms of the force balance represented by the theorem of \citet{Flierl1983}. They also noted that the eddy retained its barotropic state for a long time.
\end{itemize}
\paragraph*{Why westwards and not eastwards?}
\label{sec-6-1-2-9}
\begin{itemize}
\item Leakage and rocket force? Says that cyclones would also move westwards.
\label{sec-6-1-2-9-1}
\end{itemize}
