\subsection*{For the last two limits, can an eddy cross the shelfbreak?}
\label{sec-6-2}
\label{sec:sb}
Here, I ask whether an eddy can cross the shelfbreak and onto the shelf. The question examined in this section is similar to that tackled in \citet{Kamenkovich1996}, where, motivated by Aghulas eddies interacting with Walvis Ridge, they looked at whether eddies could cross a subsurface ridge. In their two layer study, they found that eddies that had significant vertical shear could cross a ridge, but barotropic eddies could not; indicating that the vertical scale of the eddy is of prime importance.  We shall work with the parameter,$λ$, where
\[ λ = \frac{\text{Shelfbreak depth}}{\text{Eddy vertical scale}} = \frac{\Hsb}{L_z}\]

To avoid interactions with the coastal wall, the shelf is a lot wider ($\SI{150}{km} \sim 2 \times \text{eddy radius}$) in these runs. The depth of the shelfbreak is varied so as to vary $λ$. To reduce integration time, the slopes are kept narrow ($\sim$ eddy radius).

\subsubsection*{Qualitative description}
\label{sec-6-2-1}
\paragraph*{Figure : $x-y$ maps showing different eddy behaviour for different λ\hfill{}\textsc{fig}}
\label{sec-6-2-1-1}
\begin{figure}[htb]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/paper1/sb-maps.pdf}
\caption{\label{fig:sbmap}Can the eddy cross the shelfbreak? Wildly different behaviour observed when varying λ = (shelfbreak depth)/(eddy depth scale). For a shallow shelf, the eddy leaks in a manner similar to that seen with vertical walls. For deeper shelves, the eddy tends to split into multiple eddies; each bigger that the eddies that form the leakage in the earlier case. When the shelfbreak is as deep as the eddy, the eddy crosses over onto the shelf completely.}
\end{figure}
\paragraph*{When λ \textasciitilde{} 0.25, eddy splits across shelfbreak into smaller eddies}
\label{sec-6-2-1-2}
\paragraph*{When λ \textasciitilde{} 0.65, eddy interacts with coastal wall. splits into two}
\label{sec-6-2-1-3}
\paragraph*{When λ \textasciitilde{} 1.05, "}
\label{sec-6-2-1-4}
\paragraph*{Distinguish between parent eddy being offshore but dumping more water on shelf v/s parent eddy straddling shelfbreak (latter being ridge like).}
\label{sec-6-2-1-5}
\subsubsection*{Question is more subtle}
\label{sec-6-2-2}
\paragraph*{How much of the eddy's core volume penetrates onto the shelf given an eddy vertical scale and shelfbreak depth?}
\label{sec-6-2-2-1}
\subsubsection*{When framed like this, the question is about flux of eddy water onto the shelf.}
\label{sec-6-2-3}
\subsubsection*{"When does a ridge become a wall?"}
\label{sec-6-2-4}
\subsubsection*{Bring in prior literature on eddies v/s seamounts}
\label{sec-6-2-5}
\subsubsection*{Compare against \emph{two layer} \citet{Kamenkovich1996} study and \citet{Adams2010}}
\label{sec-6-2-6}
\paragraph*{Barotropic eddies don't cross it - ✔}
\label{sec-6-2-6-1}
\paragraph*{Intensification of eddy amplitude (due to squashing?) - when crossing.}
\label{sec-6-2-6-2}
\subsubsection*{The question is whether the eddy's vertical scale is O(shelfbreak depth) when it reaches there (again, decay through radiation)}
\label{sec-6-2-7}
\subsubsection*{{\bfseries\sffamily ADD} Scaling for decay in eddy's vertical scale as it transits slope.}
\label{sec-6-2-8}
\subsubsection*{This agrees with cross-section plots in \citet{Hyun2008} - \emph{western coast}}
