\subsubsection*{Flierl, Stern \& Whitehead for western coast}
\label{sec-7-1-1}
\paragraph*{With a western coast ($H_x ≠ 0, H_y = 0$), \ref{eq:fsw} results in two conditions, $\iint ψ = \iint p_{0} = 0$ as was discussed in \citet{Flierl1987}. This means that for the system to evolve to a quasi-isolated state would require the eddy to remain surface intensified \emph{and} spin up a cyclone of equal strength. It seems reasonable to expect the second condition to be hard to satisfy. So, the eddy should always lose energy and eventually get to the shelfbreak. In fact, that is what we see in Figure \ref{fig:centrack}, with one exception.}
