\section{Discussion}
\label{sec-8}
\subsubsection*{Summarize results}
\label{sec-8-0-1}
This paper described simulations of an eddy interacting with shelf-slope topography using a continuously stratified, primitive equation model (ROMS). This is an extension of the work of \citet{Wang1992}, an exploration of the two layer ideas of \citet{LaCasce1996, Jacob2002} and a more,in-depth investigation compared to the work of \citet{Wei2009}.

I have shown that in some limits, the eddy can be prevented from crossing the slope. This occurs when an anticyclone moves towards a southern coast, or a cyclone moves towards a northern coast. This is most easily seen when (eddy width) ≪ (slope width) and most easily understood as a consequence of force balance. Isolated eddies on the $β$ plane experience a meridional force (southwards for anticyclones and vice versa) because the Coriolis force is of different magnitude at the northern and southern edges of the eddy. When the topography is configured such that it can provide a stress that opposes this meridional force, there is a possibility that they balance. Then, by the theorem of \citet{Flierl1983}, the eddy is isolated, loss of energy to wave radiation is inhibited, and the eddy moves dominantly westwards along an isobath. The key point is really the tendency to radiate waves: the theorem does not tell us about how quickly the eddy will lose energy. Previous studies have indicated that non-isolated eddies (in the sense of the theorem) tend to stay coherent longer for larger values of $U/βL^2$ \citep{LaCasce1998} or $βL/f_0$ \citep{Flierl1984}.
\paragraph*{Rationalize results of \citet{Hyun2008}, \citet{LaCasce1998}}
\label{sec-8-0-1-1}
\paragraph*{Topographic β in stratified system}
\label{sec-8-0-1-2}
In some sense, this study presents some ideas concerning the role of topographic $β$ in a continuously stratified system. For the current problem, the theorem of \citet{Flierl1983} suggests interpreting topographic $β$ as a form stress on the bottom (or side) of the eddy. This works if the bottom pressure signal can be scaled geostrophically.
\subsubsection*{Can we expect to see such behaviour in the real ocean?}
\label{sec-8-0-2}
\paragraph*{When starting with surface intensified eddies (bottom velocity $\sim$ 0), thiss balance tends to occur after quite a long time. However, in cases where the eddies start with large enough initial bottom pressure anomaly, the critical isobath is reached a lot earlier.}
\label{sec-8-0-2-1}
\begin{itemize}
\item Note that Aghulas rings have bottom velocity  \textasciitilde{} 1-3 cm/s \citep{Kamenkovich1996} and also significant bottom pressure anomalies \citet{Baker-Yeboah2010}. WCRs have \textasciitilde{} 5 cm/s (c.f. Line W sections)
\label{sec-8-0-2-1-1}
\item What about WCRs?
\label{sec-8-0-2-1-2}
\end{itemize}
\paragraph*{However, most slopes are too narrow to see this happen.}
\label{sec-8-0-2-2}
\paragraph*{Slowdown of Aghulas eddies over ridges (Byrne et al 1985) , even stalling? (Clement and Gordon, 1995) - Force balance argument?}
\label{sec-8-0-2-3}
\paragraph*{Meddies seem to stall too.}
\label{sec-8-0-2-4}
\paragraph*{Fratantoni et al. (1995) - North Brazil Current rings propagate at much slower rate than expected. \citet{Nof1996}}
\label{sec-8-0-2-5}
\paragraph*{Kuroshio rings move northward?}
\label{sec-8-0-2-6}
\paragraph*{Consequences for shelf eddies}
\label{sec-8-0-2-7}
In the simulations presented here, a balance between the bottom pressure form drag and $β$ force is seen over wide (as compared to eddy diameter) slopes. We would expect to see this over the shelf, but planetary $β$ is extremely weak there. Instead, we can ask what the theorem of \citet{Flierl1983} says about shelf eddies. For $β=0$, \ref{eq:fsw} shows that for shelf eddies to remain isolated (and live longer) they must remain surface intensified and have no integrated bottom pressure anomaly. This neglects other non-linear effects such as vortex merger and instability.
